  "opinion": "As a retired man from Bologna with a bachelor's degree and a background shaped by the educational limitations of my parents—my father with a vocational diploma and mother with only primary school education—I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can cast long shadows. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just an academic concept; it's the quiet anxiety that makes students from underrepresented groups feel their very presence in science classrooms is a challenge to their self-worth. I remember when I was young, my father would say, 'If you're not good at math, you'll never be a good engineer.' That fear, though unspoken, was a real weight. Now, as someone who has experienced the anxiety of being judged by others' expectations, I believe we must address stereotype threat in STEM. It's not about fixing the system but helping individuals feel safe and valued. In my community, we've seen how small changes—like mentorship programs that pair students with professionals who share similar backgrounds—can make a difference. These programs don't just teach science; they build confidence. I also worry about the impact of social media, where stereotypes can spread quickly and create further divisions. But with careful, community-driven efforts, we can create environments where everyone feels they belong. The key is to listen to those who have been marginalized and work alongside them to build a more inclusive future. After all, science should be for all, not just a select few.",
